BLOCK D — Advanced Server Exploitation

Objective: Learn how attackers exploit backend servers and cloud infrastructure after bypassing the web application.

Topics:

1. Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)


2. Log Poisoning




---

Topic 1 — Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)

What is SSRF?

SSRF is a vulnerability where an attacker tricks a server into making requests on the attacker's behalf.

Instead of attacking directly:

Attacker
      │
      ▼
Victim Server
      │
      ▼
Internal Resources

The server becomes the attacker's proxy.


---

Why is SSRF Dangerous?

Normally:

Attacker

❌ Cannot access

Internal Database

But with SSRF:

Attacker

↓

Victim Server

↓

Internal Database

↓

Response returned

The server has access that the attacker doesn't.


---

Example

Suppose an application fetches images.

https://example.com/fetch?url=https://abc.com/image.jpg

Developer thinks:

> "I'll download whatever URL the user provides."



Attacker changes it to:

http://127.0.0.1/admin

Now the server accesses its own internal admin page.


---

Cloud SSRF (Most Important)

Cloud providers expose a Metadata Service.

AWS example:

http://169.254.169.254/

This service may contain:

IAM Role credentials

Temporary access tokens

Instance information


If an SSRF vulnerability exists:

Attacker

↓

Application Server

↓

169.254.169.254

↓

IAM Credentials

↓

AWS Account Access

This is why SSRF is considered one of the most dangerous cloud vulnerabilities.


---

Why is SSRF Preferred by Attackers?

It allows attackers to:

Access internal services

Scan private networks

Reach cloud metadata

Bypass firewalls

Sometimes achieve Remote Code Execution



---

Types of SSRF

Basic SSRF

Server requests:

http://internal-server


---

Blind SSRF

The attacker doesn't see the response.

Instead,

they observe:

DNS lookups

Delays

External callbacks


Still useful for reconnaissance.


---

Preventing SSRF

1. Allowlist URLs

Instead of:

Any URL

Allow only:

images.company.com


---

2. Block Internal Addresses

Reject:

127.0.0.1

localhost

169.254.169.254

10.x.x.x

172.16.x.x

192.168.x.x


---

3. Network Segmentation

Ensure backend services cannot freely access every internal system.


---

4. Disable Metadata Access

Cloud providers now support:

IMDSv2 (AWS)

Metadata protections


to reduce SSRF risks.


---

Manager's WHY Question

Why is SSRF more dangerous in cloud?

Because cloud metadata services expose temporary credentials.

If attackers retrieve them,

they may gain access to cloud resources without stealing passwords.


---

Topic 2 — Log Poisoning

What is Log Poisoning?

Applications record information into logs.

Example:

IP Address

Browser

URL

Username

Errors

If user input is written to logs without validation, attackers can inject malicious content.


---

Example

Application logs:

GET /home

User-Agent:
Chrome

Attacker changes:

User-Agent:

<?php system($_GET['cmd']); ?>

The application logs it.

Later,

another vulnerability (such as LFI) causes the log file to be executed.

Now:

Attacker

↓

Injects PHP

↓

Log File

↓

LFI Includes Log

↓

PHP Executes

↓

Remote Code Execution


---

Why is Log Poisoning Dangerous?

It can lead to:

Remote Code Execution

Persistent malicious code

Hidden payloads

Forensic confusion

Tampered audit trails



---

Log Injection

Even without code execution,

attackers may manipulate logs.

Example:

Normal log:

Login Failed

User: John

Attacker injects:

Login Successful

Admin Access Granted

Now investigators may misinterpret events.


---

Why Sanitize Logs?

Logs are used for:

Incident Response

SIEM

Compliance

Forensics


If attackers can manipulate them,

security teams may make incorrect decisions.


---

Preventing Log Poisoning

Validate Input

Never write raw user input directly into logs.


---

Encode Special Characters

Prevent execution of injected code.


---

Least Privilege

Logs should not be executable.


---

Secure Log Storage

Use:

Centralized logging

Append-only logs

Immutable storage



---

Manager's WHY Question

Why sanitize log entries?

Because logs are trusted during investigations.

If attackers can inject or manipulate log content,

they can hide attacks, mislead investigators, or exploit other vulnerabilities.


---

Enterprise Example (Barclays)

Suppose an internal AI service logs every request.

Bad implementation:

Prompt:

<User Input>

Attacker submits malicious input.

↓

Logs store it.

↓

Another service processes logs unsafely.

↓

Potential compromise.

Good implementation:

Escape special characters.

Validate input.

Store logs securely.

Restrict access.



